               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18470614-name-1093" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18470614-name-1093" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18470614-name-1093" type="surname" value="DAVIS"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18470614-name-1093" type="given" value="THOMAS"></interp>THOMAS DAVIS</persName>
                  </hi> I live in Sun-alley, Woolwich, and am a sawyer. On 26th of May, about eight o'clock in the morning, I went into the White Lion public-house—the prisoner was there in the parlour—I took my watch out of my pocket to wind it up—the prisoner said he would take it to the bar, and have it put to rights for me—I said, "No, let it alone; I shall put it to rights myself"—he took it out of my hand, and went off with it.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="italic">Prisoner.</hi> He gave it into my hand, and told me to go and pawn it. <hi rend="italic">Witness</hi> No, I did not—he did not bring anything back for it—I was not the worse for liquor—I have known him ever since he was born—I thought he might bring it back.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18470614-name-1094" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18470614-name-1094" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18470614-name-1094" type="surname" value="BARTON"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18470614-name-1094" type="given" value="GEORGE"></interp>GEORGE BARTON</persName>
                  </hi>. I am in the employ of Mr. Carter, a pawnbroker, at Greenwich. On the 26th of May the prisoner came, and brought this watch—he pawned it for 12<hi rend="italic">s</hi>., in the name of Thomas Smith—he said it was his own.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
